# 2️⃣ AWS Account Setup

### Step 1: Sign Up for AWS

**Visit the AWS Website:**  
Go to the official AWS website: [AWS Sign Up](https://aws.amazon.com/).

**Click “Create an AWS Account”:**  
On the homepage, click the **"Create an AWS Account"** button.

**Enter Your Information:**  
- **Email Address**: Enter your email address.
- **Password**: Create a secure password.
- **AWS Account Name**: Choose an account name (e.g., `Your_Account_Name`).

**Agree to the Terms and Conditions:**  
Review and agree to AWS's terms and conditions.

---

### Step 2: Provide Payment Information

**Enter Payment Details:**  
- AWS requires a valid credit card for verification purposes, even for the Free Tier.
- AWS will not charge you unless you exceed the Free Tier limits.

**Billing Address:**  
Enter your billing address and contact information.

**Verify Payment Information:**  
AWS may charge a small amount (typically a few dollars) to verify your payment method. This charge will be refunded.

---

### Step 3: Identity Verification

**Verify Your Identity:**  
- AWS may ask you to verify your identity through a phone call or text message.
- You will receive a verification code on your phone, which you need to enter to proceed.

---

### Step 4: Select Your Support Plan

**Choose a Support Plan:**  
- Select the **Basic Support Plan** for free access to AWS support.
- You can choose a higher-tier plan if you need premium support (this comes at an additional cost).

---

### Step 5: Access Your AWS Management Console

**Sign In to the AWS Console:**  
Once your account is set up, you can sign in to the **AWS Management Console** at [AWS Console](https://aws.amazon.com/console/).

- Enter your **email address** and **password**.
- You will be taken to the main dashboard where you can start exploring AWS services.

---

### Step 6: Set Up IAM (Identity and Access Management)

**Create IAM Users (Recommended):**  
- It's a best practice not to use your root user for everyday tasks. Instead, create **IAM (Identity and Access Management)** users with appropriate permissions.
- From the AWS Management Console, go to the **IAM Dashboard** and create new users. Assign them necessary roles and permissions.
